You said:
KK Rantau Panjang (1).svg
File
how do i make this picture become an interactive file, where there are clickable areas. when we click on that area it will pop up another picture (live advertisement but with close button on it). when done with that popped up picture, we can close it and click at different area
ChatGPT said:

Got it 👍 You uploaded an SVG file, and you want to make it interactive so that:

  • Specific areas on the picture can be clicked.

  • When clicked, a popup window (with another picture, like an advertisement) appears.

  • The popup should have a close button.

  • After closing, you can click other areas to open different popups.

This can be done with HTML + CSS + JavaScript by embedding your SVG and defining clickable regions.

Here’s a simple example structure I can adapt for your file:

html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
  <meta charset="UTF-8">
  <title>Interactive SVG Map</title>
  <style>
    body {
      font-family: Arial, sans-serif;
    }
    .popup {
      display: none;
      position: fixed;
      top: 0;
      left: 0;
      width: 100%;
      height: 100%;
      background: rgba(0,0,0,0.7);
      justify-content: center;
      align-items: center;
    }
    .popup-content {
      position: relative;
      background: #fff;
      padding: 10px;
      border-radius: 10px;
      max-width: 80%;
      max-height: 80%;
    }
    .popup-content img {
      max-width: 100%;
      max-height: 100%;
    }
    .close-btn {
      position: absolute;
      top: 5px;
      right: 10px;
      font-size: 20px;
      cursor: pointer;
      color: red;
    }
    svg {
      width: 100%;
      height: auto;
    }
    .clickable {
      cursor: pointer;
      fill-opacity: 0; /* keeps it transparent but clickable */
    }
  </style>
</head>
<body>

  <!-- Embed your SVG -->
  <div>
    <!-- Example clickable area -->
    <svg xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" width="600" height="400">
      <rect x="50" y="50" width="100" height="100" class="clickable" onclick="openPopup('ad1.jpg')"/>
      <circle cx="300" cy="200" r="50" class="clickable" onclick="openPopup('ad2.jpg')"/>
    </svg>
  </div>

  <!-- Popup -->
  <div id="popup" class="popup">
    <div class="popup-content">
      <span class="close-btn" onclick="closePopup()">&times;</span>
      <img id="popup-img" src="" alt="Advertisement">
    </div>
  </div>

  <script>
    function openPopup(imgSrc) {
      document.getElementById("popup-img").src = imgSrc;
      document.getElementById("popup").style.display = "flex";
    }
    function closePopup() {
      document.getElementById("popup").style.display = "none";
      document.getElementById("popup-img").src = "";
    }
  </script>

</body>
</html>

How it works:

  • Add class="clickable" to the areas of your SVG you want clickable.

  • Use onclick="openPopup('image.jpg')" to define which image should show.

  • A popup div will display the selected image, with a close button.

You said:
if i want to share this to other person, where do i park this file? is it sufficient i park it in my google drive? or need to have a server or website?
ChatGPT said:

Good question 👍

It depends on how you want people to use the interactive file:

1. Just for viewing on their own computer

  • You can put the HTML file (with your SVG + popup code) in Google Drive, OneDrive, or even send it by email.

  • The person just downloads it and opens it in a browser (Chrome, Edge, Firefox).
    ✅ No server needed.
    ⚠️ But if your popups load external images (e.g., ad1.jpg), you must include those images together with the HTML file in the same folder.

2. For people to click a link and view online

  • Google Drive is not good for this, because it usually forces a download instead of showing the page as a live website.

  • You’ll need a place that can serve HTML pages directly. Examples:

    • GitHub Pages (free, perfect for hosting interactive HTML files).

    • Netlify (free plan, drag-and-drop upload).

    • Vercel (free, simple).

    • Your own web hosting / server.

With these, you just share a URL (e.g., https://yourname.github.io/interactive-map) and anyone can open it like a website.

3. If it’s for internal staff only

  • You can host the file on your organization’s intranet server.

  • Or just share the zipped HTML + image files by email/Google Drive and tell them to open in a browser.

✨ So:

  • For quick sharing (offline use) → Google Drive (but must download).

  • For online interactive viewing → Better to use GitHub Pages / Netlify / Vercel (free & easy).

ChatGPT said:

Great choice 👍 GitHub Pages is simple and free.

🚦 Limitations of GitHub Pages

  • Traffic / Bandwidth: GitHub doesn’t publish exact limits, but in practice it’s very generous. People have hosted popular open-source project sites there with thousands of visitors a day without issues.

  • Concurrent users: There’s no strict “number of people at the same time” limit. It’s backed by GitHub’s content delivery network (CDN), so it scales well for normal use.

  • File size: Each repository has a 1 GB limit, and GitHub Pages recommends keeping your site under 1 GB in total. Individual file size is limited to 100 MB.

  • No backend code: It only serves static files (HTML, CSS, JS, images). No PHP, databases, or server-side scripts.

✅ For your interactive SVG with popups → it’s perfect. Even hundreds of people can view it at once with no problem.

🛠 Step-by-Step: Publish Your File on GitHub Pages

  1. Create a GitHub account (if you don’t already) → https://github.com.

  2. Create a new repository:

    • Click the ➕ New repo button.

    • Name it something like interactive-map.

    • Set it Public (so others can see it).

    • Leave the rest default, then Create repository.

  3. Upload your files:

    • Go into the new repo.

    • Click Add file → Upload files.

    • Upload:

      • Your index.html (the main file with the SVG + popup code).

      • All images you want to show in the popups (e.g., ad1.jpg, ad2.jpg).

    • Click Commit changes.

  4. Enable GitHub Pages:

    • Go to Settings (top menu of your repo).

    • Scroll to Pages (left sidebar).

    • Under Branch, select main (or master) and /root.

    • Click Save.

  5. Get your link 🎉

    • After a few minutes, GitHub Pages will give you a link like:

      perl
      https://yourusername.github.io/interactive-map/

    • Share this link with anyone → they can open it directly in a browser.

Nice — I’ve got a simple, reliable way for you to pick coordinates directly on the image in the browser, preview the hotspot, and then either add it live or copy the exact CSS snippet to paste into your index.html in the repo.

Below I give you:

  1. a short explanation of the best approach (percentages → responsive),

  2. a ready-to-drop index.html that includes a coordinate picker UI (draw a rectangle, type the popup filename like rx1.png, click Add hotspot or Copy snippet), and

  3. quick steps to make the change permanent on GitHub.

Why use percentages

Use percentages for top, left, width, height (instead of pixels). That keeps the hotspots in the right place even if the image resizes on different screens.

Percent formula used in the tool:

  • left% = (leftPx / displayedImageWidth) * 100

  • top% = (topPx / displayedImageHeight) * 100

  • width% = (rectWidth / displayedImageWidth) * 100

  • height% = (rectHeight / displayedImageHeight) * 100

<script>
  /* --- popup functions --- */
  function openPopup(imgSrc) {
    document.getElementById('popup-img').src = imgSrc;
    const popup = document.getElementById('popup');
    popup.style.display = 'flex';
    popup.setAttribute('aria-hidden','false');
  }
  function closePopup() {
    document.getElementById('popup-img').src = '';
    const popup = document.getElementById('popup');
    popup.style.display = 'none';
    popup.setAttribute('aria-hidden','true');
  }

  /* --- coordinate picker and hotspot creator --- */
  const toggleBtn = document.getElementById('togglePick');
  const mapImg = document.getElementById('mapImg');
  const container = document.getElementById('mapContainer');
  const popupFileInput = document.getElementById('popupFile');
  const snippetBox = document.getElementById('snippet');
  const copyBtn = document.getElementById('copySnippetBtn');
  const addHotspotBtn = document.getElementById('addHotspotBtn');
  const hotspotList = document.getElementById('hotspotList');

  let picking = false;
  let dragging = false;
  let startX=0, startY=0;
  let previewEl = null;
  let lastRect = null; // {leftPct, topPct, widthPct, heightPct}

  toggleBtn.addEventListener('click', () => {
    picking = !picking;
    toggleBtn.textContent = picking ? 'Disable coordinate picker' : 'Enable coordinate picker';
    toggleBtn.style.background = picking ? '#ffefef' : '';
  });

  // Helper: get coordinates relative to image (displayed)
  function clientToImageCoords(clientX, clientY) {
    const rect = mapImg.getBoundingClientRect();
    const x = clientX - rect.left;
    const y = clientY - rect.top;
    return { x, y, width: rect.width, height: rect.height };
  }

  // mousedown -> start preview
  mapImg.addEventListener('mousedown', (ev) => {
    if (!picking) return;
    ev.preventDefault();
    dragging = true;
    const pos = clientToImageCoords(ev.clientX, ev.clientY);
    startX = pos.x;
    startY = pos.y;
    previewEl = document.createElement('div');
    previewEl.className = 'hotspot-preview';
    previewEl.style.left = startX + 'px';
    previewEl.style.top  = startY + 'px';
    previewEl.style.width = '0px';
    previewEl.style.height = '0px';
    container.appendChild(previewEl);
  });

  // mousemove -> update preview
  window.addEventListener('mousemove', (ev) => {
    if (!dragging || !previewEl) return;
    const pos = clientToImageCoords(ev.clientX, ev.clientY);
    const rect = mapImg.getBoundingClientRect();
    let left = Math.min(startX, pos.x), top = Math.min(startY, pos.y);
    let w = Math.abs(pos.x - startX), h = Math.abs(pos.y - startY);
    // clamp inside image
    left = Math.max(0, Math.min(left, rect.width));
    top  = Math.max(0, Math.min(top, rect.height));
    w = Math.max(0, Math.min(w, rect.width - left));
    h = Math.max(0, Math.min(h, rect.height - top));
    previewEl.style.left = left + 'px';
    previewEl.style.top  = top  + 'px';
    previewEl.style.width = w + 'px';
    previewEl.style.height = h + 'px';
  });

  // mouseup -> finalize and show snippet
  window.addEventListener('mouseup', (ev) => {
    if (!dragging) return;
    dragging = false;
    if (!previewEl) return;
    const rect = mapImg.getBoundingClientRect();
    const leftPx = parseFloat(previewEl.style.left);
    const topPx  = parseFloat(previewEl.style.top);
    const wPx = parseFloat(previewEl.style.width);
    const hPx = parseFloat(previewEl.style.height);
    // Convert to percentages
    const leftPct = (leftPx / rect.width * 100).toFixed(3);
    const topPct  = (topPx  / rect.height * 100).toFixed(3);
    const wPct    = (wPx    / rect.width * 100).toFixed(3);
    const hPct    = (hPx    / rect.height * 100).toFixed(3);

    lastRect = { leftPct, topPct, wPct, hPct };
    const suggestedFile = popupFileInput.value || 'rx1.png';

    const snippet = `<div class="clickable" style="top:${topPct}%; left:${leftPct}%; width:${wPct}%; height:${hPct}%;"
  onclick="openPopup('${suggestedFile}')"></div>`;

    snippetBox.value = snippet;
    // keep preview until user clicks Add or toggles picker off
  });

  // Add hotspot to page (live, not saved to repo)
  addHotspotBtn.addEventListener('click', () => {
    if (!lastRect) { alert('Draw a rectangle first'); return; }
    const file = popupFileInput.value || 'rx1.png';
    const div = document.createElement('div');
    div.className = 'clickable';
    div.style.top = lastRect.topPct + '%';
    div.style.left = lastRect.leftPct + '%';
    div.style.width = lastRect.wPct + '%';
    div.style.height = lastRect.hPct + '%';
    div.addEventListener('click', () => openPopup(file));
    container.appendChild(div);
    addHotspotItemToList(lastRect, file);
    // clear preview
    if (previewEl) { previewEl.remove(); previewEl = null; }
    lastRect = null;
    snippetBox.value = '';
  });

  // Copy snippet to clipboard
  copyBtn.addEventListener('click', async () => {
    if (!snippetBox.value) { alert('Draw a rectangle first'); return; }
    try {
      await navigator.clipboard.writeText(snippetBox.value);
      copyBtn.textContent = 'Copied!';
      setTimeout(()=>copyBtn.textContent='Copy snippet', 1200);
    } catch (e) {
      alert('Cannot copy automatically — select and copy the snippet manually.');
    }
  });

  // show added hotspot in list with delete option
  function addHotspotItemToList(rect, file) {
    const item = document.createElement('div');
    item.className = 'hotspot-item';
    const left = `${rect.leftPct}%`, top = `${rect.topPct}%`;
    const wh = `${rect.wPct}% × ${rect.hPct}%`;
    item.innerHTML = `<div><strong>${file}</strong><br><small>${left} / ${top} / ${wh}</small></div>`;
    const delBtn = document.createElement('button');
    delBtn.className = 'btn';
    delBtn.textContent = 'Remove';
    delBtn.addEventListener('click', () => {
      // remove one clickable that matches coordinates + file
      const list = Array.from(container.querySelectorAll('.clickable'));
      for (let el of list) {
        if (el.style.top === (rect.topPct + '%') && el.style.left === (rect.leftPct + '%') &&
            el.style.width === (rect.wPct + '%') && el.style.height === (rect.hPct + '%')) {
          el.remove();
          break;
        }
      }
      item.remove();
    });
    item.appendChild(delBtn);
    hotspotList.appendChild(item);
  }

  // Prevent image drag interfering
  mapImg.addEventListener('dragstart', e=>e.preventDefault());
</script>

</body>
</html>

How to use this page (quick)

  1. Open your site (the GitHub Pages link) or open index.html locally in a browser.

  2. Click Enable coordinate picker.

  3. Click and drag on the map where RX1 is — you’ll see a dashed rectangle.

  4. Enter the popup image filename (e.g. rx1.png) in Popup image.

  5. Click Add hotspot to place it live on the page (this does not save to GitHub repo) — or click Copy snippet to copy the HTML snippet.

  6. To make it permanent: edit index.html in your repo and paste the copied <div class="clickable" ...> inside the .map-container (so it appears alongside other hotspots). Commit the change. Wait a minute and refresh the published site.

<div class="clickable" style="top:28.345%; left:41.002%; width:8.172%; height:6.314%;"
     onclick="openPopup('rx1.png')"></div>
